All Life Customer Segmentaion¶

Background:¶

This work shows segmentation analysis of All Life Bank credit card customers in order to:

  1. Improve current existing marketing
  2. Help in new customers targeting
  3. Improve customer service

Objective:¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

Key Questions to answer:¶

  1. How many different segments of customers are there
  2. How are these segments different from each other
  3. Possible recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers

Data Description:¶

  • Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

Elbow method¶

In [26]:
#Finding optimal no. of clusters
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist

clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(df_z)
    prediction=model.predict(df_z)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df_z, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / df_z
                           .shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'go-')
plt.xlabel('k', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Average distortion', fontsize=14)
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method', fontsize=16)
Out[26]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

Based on Elbow plot 6 clusters can be applied to have relatively small distance of 1 between the clusters centroids (based on Euclidean distanse).

  • Average trends are: high number of credit cards together with online visits; low number of credit cards with high number of calls made (can be less 'happy' customers).
  • Total trends are: bank visits made is decreasing from from the customers with high number of credit cards ('happy' customers) to the customers with low number of credit cards (less 'happy' customers).
  • Differences between two methods: are on smaller 'unhappy' groups #2, #0 and #5 for KMeans and #0, #2, and #1 for Hierarchical in terms of number of credit cards and communication means. These groups need more attention. Since KMeans gave higher Silhouette score with 6 groups, it is chosen for final analysis.

Conclusions:¶

  1. How many different segments of customers: 6 different segment were found.

  2. Main differences between these segments and recommendatiions:

    • Avg Credit Limit and Total number of credit cards is higher for the first three groups ('happy' customers), with different communication means: 'onliners' with the highest Credit Limit and credit cards; and two groups with 6 credit cards and about 45,000 credit limit, where one group made highest number of bank visits ('onsiters').

      • Recommendation to the bank: incraese online advertisement for the first group and incraese onsite advertisement for the latest group (among these three).

    • Avg Credit Limit and Total number of credit cards is low for the last three groups ('unhappy' customers), also with different communication means. These groups need more customer support and marketing attention in general.

    • Two groups with realtively high number of calls made and online visitors, about 2 credit cards on average.
      • Recommendation to the bank: phone marketing maybe helpful.
    • Group with 6 credit cards and very low communicators - they prefer making bank visits:
      • Recommendation to the bank: onsite marketing and increased onsite attention maybe helpful.
